{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566410"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18821"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18821"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.15,0.14,0.22,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11554"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90023"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1221"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8823"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27192"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of burning and gritty sensation in both eyes. He reports frequent episodes of watery eyes and blurred vision that improves with blinking. He also has pustules over his cheeks and nose with erythema, and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His eyelid margins are thickened and telangiectatic. There is meibomian gland dysfunction with inspissated glands. The conjunctiva is mildly injected bilaterally. The cornea shows superficial punctate keratopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral doxycycline","Lid massage","Topical antibiotics","Topical corticosteroids","Oral acyclovir"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of ocular rosacea, which commonly occurs in patients with cutaneous rosacea as demonstrated by the pustules and erythema. The condition affects the meibomian glands and ocular surface, leading to symptoms of ocular surface disease. This may be with blepharitis, conjunctivitis, meibomian gland dysfunction, tearing, photophobia, recurrent chalazia and burning sensation in the eye and the variance can make it difficult to diagnosis. It is a chronic inflammatory disease and more common in women aged 30 - 60 years of age with light complexions. It affects up to 10% of the population so is a rather common and manageable condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline \u003C/strong\u003Etogether with lid hygiene and artificial tears is the most appropriate management plan. Doxycycline has both antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties, and at a sub-antimicrobial dose (50-100mg daily) effectively reduces inflammation and improves meibomian gland function. Lid hygiene (warm eye compress and eyelid wet tissues) and artificial tears provide essential supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELid massage\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while potentially helpful as part of lid hygiene routine, would be insufficient for managing ocular rosacea of this severity. While it may help express the meibomian glands, it does not address the underlying inflammatory process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E might provide temporary relief but are not recommended for long-term management due to potential complications including glaucoma and cataract formation. They also do not address the underlying meibomian gland dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective in managing ocular rosacea as the condition is primarily inflammatory rather than infectious. They do not address the underlying pathophysiology of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this is not a viral condition. It is used for herpes simplex keratitis, which typically presents with dendritic ulcers rather than the diffuse surface changes seen in rosacea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ocular rosacea requires both topical and systemic therapy for effective management.","Oral tetracyclines are first-line systemic therapy for ocular rosacea due to their anti-inflammatory properties.","Artificial tears and lid hygiene are essential supportive measures in ocular rosacea management."],"references":["Khadamy J. Ocular Rosacea: Don\u0027t Forget Eyelids and Skin in the Assessment of This Stubborn Ocular Surface Disease. Cureus. 2024.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10828744/","Rodrigues-Braz D, Zhao M, Yesilirmak N, Aractingi S, Behar-Cohen F, Bourges JL. Cutaneous and ocular rosacea: Common and specific physiopathogenic mechanisms and study models. Mol Vis. 2021.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8131178/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90023"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90023"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:34:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:37:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11554"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co